 the role of English in the global context: the ‘centrality of structure’, ‘relationships of interdependence’, ‘social constructions of difference’ and ‘reproduction of inequality’. These themes enable the authors to draw attention to the dynamics of the contemporary realities of the ‘English-speaking’ and ‘English-using’ nations, especially as they compete for cultural, social, economic and symbolic capital in global networks. In engaging World Englishes with the sociolinguistics of globalization, the authors raise some fundamental questions about the status, structure, and functions of World Englishes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh  aEnglish as a global language.  aEnglish as a lingua franca.  aEnglish.  aGlobal English.  aGlobalisation.  aGlobalization.  aGlocalization of English.  aInternational English.  aInternational Englishes.  aInternational communication.  aSociolinguistics.  aWorld Englishes.1 aBhatt, Rakesh M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBobda, Augustin Simo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChew, Phyllis Ghim-Lian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewey, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorgieva, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNihalani, Paroo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOmoniyi, Tope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOmoniyi, Tope, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPennycook, Alastair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo